{"author":{"id":"222a064dabc38896d34e2f40eca4106beb1a3fa7dfe16ff52f0598bf0153ef39"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1594906111,"nonce":"G4hW1/xwTl8V51/IkZEsy1mZqhI=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY1OTQxMTc4Mw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3111#issuecomment-659411783"},"message":"The issue appears to be with elink/efetch. You cannot provide a history from elink to it.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1595002550,"nonce":"JkWRai2w4wX9UaWdj5ycjcYKLuo=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY2MDE5NzcwOA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3111#issuecomment-660197708"},"message":"Just a further clarification/correction...\n\nYes, esearch-\u003eefetch via history works, but if you search (e.g.) the \"gene\" db, and want the linked \"nuccore\" fasta records associated with the gene db's UIDs that are returned, you have to go through elink (I thought it was notable that if you enter N gene UIDs and select \"nuccore\" in efetch, instead of getting no results, you get what appear to be the first N records from nuccore in some sort of alphanumeric order - which is perhaps understandable, but a bit confusing for an inexperienced user).\n\nGoing through elink, you can get either json or xml (it does not currently return a file of UIDs).  If you provide that elink history output to efetch, in either case, you get a red/empty collection.  The json(/xml?) structure output by elink puts webenv and querykey in a place that the tools-iuc eutils suite does not currently parse.\n\nThe only way in galaxy currently to provide elink output to efetch is the history (though perhaps it can be changed to output an ID list file?).  The efetch galaxy tool allows you to select the elink history output when you change the output to json(/xml?), but since none of the IDs, webenv, or query_key items are successfully parsed out by efetch.py, it cannot supply those items in the payload and the red/empty collection is the result.\n\nI was incorrect in my initial assessment of the biopython Entrez package's efetch code (python's not my native language). It will succeed if you pass it a value for webenv and query_key (and no `id` value) in the payload.  So the issue is just obtaining those values from the elink output and putting them in the payload supplied to Entrez.efetch.\n\nSince webenv strings expire, it might be a good idea to at least convert the elink output into a ID list file and offer the history (json/xml) as an optional output.","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1595007292,"nonce":"IrfUKx4ozVxa5uB6nirvD+USqEs=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlQ29tbWVudEVkaXQ6Mzg2NjgyMjYy"},"target":"4570287431ebf0cc9741a47af4e83672071fc9f84fe5224f941307044a6d199e","message":"Just a further clarification/correction...\n\nYes, esearch-\u003eefetch via history works, but if you search (e.g.) the \"gene\" db, and want the linked \"nuccore\" fasta records associated with the gene db's UIDs that are returned, you have to go through elink (I thought it was notable that if you enter N gene UIDs and select \"nuccore\" in efetch, instead of getting no results, you get what appear to be the first N records from nuccore in some sort of alphanumeric order - which is perhaps understandable, but a bit confusing for an inexperienced user).\n\nGoing through elink, you can get either json or xml (it does not currently return a file of UIDs).  If you provide that elink history output to efetch, in either case, you get a red/empty collection.  The json(/xml?) structure output by elink puts webenv and querykey in a place that the tools-iuc eutils suite does not currently parse.\n\nThe only way in galaxy currently to provide elink output to efetch is the history (though perhaps elink can be changed to output an ID list file or have efetch parse the elink input?).  The efetch galaxy tool allows you to select the elink history output when you change the elink output to json(/xml?), but since none of the IDs, webenv, or query_key items are successfully parsed, efetch cannot supply those items in the payload and the red/empty collection is the result.\n\nI was incorrect in my initial assessment of the biopython Entrez package's efetch code (python's not my native language). It will succeed if you pass it a value for webenv and query_key (and no `id` value) in the payload.  So the issue is just obtaining those values from the elink output and putting them in the payload supplied to Entrez.efetch.\n\nSince webenv strings expire, it might be a good idea to at least convert the elink output into a ID list file and offer the history (json/xml) as an optional output.","files":null}]}